La modalità notturna migliora significativamente le foto scattate in ambienti poco illuminati, riducendo il rumore e migliorando la nitidezza. La ricarica rapida da 33W è un ulteriore vantaggio, permettendo di ricaricare completamente la batteria in circa un'ora.#### SoftwareIl POCO X6 Pro utilizza MIUI, la skin personalizzata di Xiaomi basata su Android. Ecco le mie impressioni dopo diverse settimane di utilizzo.Design e CostruzioneIl POCO X6 Pro presenta un design elegante e moderno, con una costruzione solida che conferisce una sensazione di robustezza. La parte posteriore in vetro e il telaio in metallo offrono un aspetto premium che è difficile da trovare in questa fascia di prezzo. Il dispositivo è disponibile in diverse colorazioni vivaci che lo rendono attraente a prima vista.#### DisplayIl display del POCO X6 Pro è uno dei suoi punti di forza. Con un pannello AMOLED da 6,67 pollici e una risoluzione Full HD+, le immagini sono nitide e i colori vivaci. La frequenza di aggiornamento di 120 Hz garantisce una fluidità eccezionale nelle animazioni e nello scrolling, migliorando l'esperienza utente sia nei giochi che nella navigazione quotidiana.#### PrestazioniEquipaggiato con un processore Snapdragon 870 e 8 GB di RAM, il POCO X6 Pro offre prestazioni eccellenti. Le applicazioni si aprono rapidamente e il multitasking è fluido. Ho testato diversi giochi ad alte prestazioni e il telefono ha gestito tutto senza problemi, senza rallentamenti o surriscaldamenti eccessivi. Anche le applicazioni più impegnative funzionano senza intoppi, rendendo questo dispositivo ideale per gli utenti più esigenti.#### FotocameraIl comparto fotografico del POCO X6 Pro è sorprendentemente buono per la sua fascia di prezzo. La fotocamera principale da 64 MP cattura immagini dettagliate e vivide in condizioni di buona illuminazione. La modalità notturna migliora significativamente le foto scattate in ambienti poco illuminati, riducendo il rumore e migliorando la nitidezza. La fotocamera grandangolare e il sensore macro aggiungono versatilità al sistema fotografico, permettendo di catturare una varietà di scatti diversi.#### BatteriaLa batteria da 5000 mAh del POCO X6 Pro offre un'autonomia eccellente. Con un uso moderato, il telefono dura facilmente due giorni con una sola carica. Anche con un uso intensivo, tra cui sessioni di gaming e streaming video, il dispositivo riesce a coprire un'intera giornata senza problemi. L'interfaccia è ricca di funzionalità e personalizzazioni, anche se potrebbe risultare un po' pesante per chi preferisce un'esperienza Android più stock. Tuttavia, MIUI è fluida e offre molte opzioni per adattare il telefono alle proprie esigenze.#### PrezzoIl POCO X6 Pro offre un rapporto qualità-prezzo eccezionale. Con specifiche e prestazioni paragonabili a dispositivi di fascia più alta, il prezzo competitivo lo rende una scelta eccellente per chi cerca un telefono potente senza spendere una fortuna.#### ConclusioniIn conclusione, il POCO X6 Pro è uno smartphone che offre prestazioni elevate, un display eccellente e una buona qualità costruttiva a un prezzo molto competitivo. È ideale per chi cerca un dispositivo versatile, capace di gestire sia le attività quotidiane che i giochi più impegnativi. I have the 2019 Xperia 1, and I tend to play a lot of emulators on this device since the Snapdragon 855 is still very solid for emulation and more in 2021.  I didn't want to deal with Bluetooth due to input lag, so I was hoping for a true controller that can plus into USB C and I can have everything on my hands.  I saw a video of the earlier generation X2 from Retro Game Corps's YouTube page, and the X2 caught my attention.  GameSir stated that Xperia 1 phones will work on their device, and thus I did an order.Glad I did, it is excellent for my needs.  I was worried that the placement of the D-Pad being below the left analog stick will be an issue, but it wasn't a problem at all.  It is a good D-Pad that is great for 2D games.  Is it the best?  No, but most people won't have an issue with it.  The buttons are solid and so are the analog sticks.  Most people who will run it for emulation will not have an problem with the unit.  Since the button layout is the Nintendo layout (not XBox layout which is common on Android apps), you will have to adjust the button layout on a program/game.  Not all games support changing buttons, so you might have issues with the button layout using this.  If you are into racing games, the R2/L2 buttons are digital buttons and not analog.Due to how wide the Xperia 1 phones are, you will have to stretch out the X2 to its limit in order to put the Xperia in the X2.  The USB C connector on the X2 is great since it moves up and down, which will help reduce stress on the USB C connector on your phones.  While the X2 will work with most phone cases, I would be careful and not use the X2 with the Xperia 1 phones with thick cases.  I currently have the Spigen Rugged Armor Case for the Xperia 1 and it is not a thick case at all.  I was able to put the Xperia 1 in the X2 with this case on, but any thicker phone case it wouldn't fit.  But if the phone was smaller then the Xperia 1 with a phone case that is thicker then it should fit just fine on the X2.There is also an USB-C connector at the bottom left corner of the X2, since it is a pass-thru USB-C Connector.  You can use it for charging or anything you want to use it for USB-C wise.  Almost forgot, since the USB C connector on the X2 will be on the left side, some apps may not work since they are used to be in horizontal mode when the USB C connector is on its right side.X2 is pricey, but I gotta admit with the Xperia 1 in the X2 it feels great, my hands don't hurt when using it, and just feels solid.  If you do a lot of emulation of gaming with a D-Pad that supports different controllers, then I highly recommend the X2 new edition with the D-Pad.  Also gets a plus for me since it supports the Xperia 1 phones and its weird aspect ratio.

I didn't want to deal with Bluetooth due to input lag, so I was hoping for a true controller that can plus into USB C and I can have everything on my hands.  I saw a video of the earlier generation X2 from Retro Game Corps's YouTube page, and the X2 caught my attention.  GameSir stated that Xperia 1 phones will work on their device, and thus I did an order.Glad I did, it is excellent for my needs.  I was worried that the placement of the D-Pad being below the left analog stick will be an issue, but it wasn't a problem at all.  It is a good D-Pad that is great for 2D games.  Is it the best?  No, but most people won't have an issue with it.  The buttons are solid and so are the analog sticks.  Most people who will run it for emulation will not have an problem with the unit. If you are into racing games, the R2/L2 buttons are digital buttons and not analog.Due to how wide the Xperia 1 phones are, you will have to stretch out the X2 to its limit in order to put the Xperia in the X2.  The USB C connector on the X2 is great since it moves up and down, which will help reduce stress on the USB C connector on your phones.  While the X2 will work with most phone cases, I would be careful and not use the X2 with the Xperia 1 phones with thick cases.  I currently have the Spigen Rugged Armor Case for the Xperia 1 and it is not a thick case at all.  I was able to put the Xperia 1 in the X2 with this case on, but any thicker phone case it wouldn't fit.  But if the phone was smaller then the Xperia 1 with a phone case that is thicker then it should fit just fine on the X2.There is also an USB-C connector at the bottom left corner of the X2, since it is a pass-thru USB-C Connector.  You can use it for charging or anything you want to use it for USB-C wise.  Almost forgot, since the USB C connector on the X2 will be on the left side, some apps may not work since they are used to be in horizontal mode when the USB C connector is on its right side.X2 is pricey, but I gotta admit with the Xperia 1 in the X2 it feels great, my hands don't hurt when using it, and just feels solid.  If you do a lot of emulation of gaming with a D-Pad that supports different controllers, then I highly recommend the X2 new edition with the D-Pad.  Also gets a plus for me since it supports the Xperia 1 phones and its weird aspect ratio.

The 512GB of internal storage provides ample space for apps, media, and files, making it ideal for power users.### CameraOne of the standout features of the S24 Ultra is its camera system. The quad-camera setup includes a 200MP main sensor, ultra-wide, telephoto, and periscope lenses. The camera delivers exceptional photo and video quality, with sharp details, accurate colors, and impressive low-light performance. The zoom capabilities, up to 100x, allow for capturing distant subjects with surprising clarity.### Battery LifeThe phone boasts a 5000mAh battery, which comfortably lasts a full day of heavy usage. The inclusion of fast charging, both wired and wireless, means you can quickly top up the battery when needed. Additionally, the S24 Ultra supports reverse wireless charging, allowing you to charge other devices on the go.### SoftwareRunning on Samsung’s One UI over Android 14, the Galaxy S24 Ultra provides a smooth and intuitive user interface. Samsung’s software suite offers plenty of customization options and useful features, although some users might find the pre-installed apps and bloatware unnecessary.### Connectivity and ExtrasThe S24 Ultra supports 5G connectivity, ensuring fast data speeds and future-proofing your device. It also includes other high-end features like an under-display fingerprint scanner, facial recognition, and IP68 water and dust resistance. The lack of a headphone jack might be a downside for some, but it’s a common trend in modern smartphones.### PriceAs a flagship device, the Galaxy S24 Ultra comes with a premium price tag. The 512GB model, in particular, is an investment, but it justifies the cost with its high-end specifications and features. It’s an excellent choice for those who demand the best in performance, camera quality, and storage capacity.### ConclusionThe Samsung Galaxy S24 Ultra 512GB is a powerhouse smartphone that excels in nearly every aspect. From its stunning display and powerful performance to its versatile camera system and ample storage, it’s designed to meet the needs of demanding users. While the price is high and the size may not suit everyone, it stands out as one of the best smartphones available in 2024.
